      <h2>Regular Cleaning</h2>
      <p>Wipe the exterior with a soft dry cloth after every use to remove dust and moisture from hands. For the keyboard use a slightly damp cloth (not wet) to clean keys — never use chemical cleaners which can damage the ivory or synthetic key surface. Clean the interior once every 6 months using a soft brush to remove accumulated dust from around the reeds.</p>

      <h2>Storage Essentials</h2>
      <p>Always store harmonium in its protective case when not in use. Keep away from direct sunlight which causes wood to warp and keys to yellow or crack. Avoid storing in very humid areas (above 70% humidity causes bellows leather to deteriorate and reeds to develop moisture damage) or very dry environments (below 30% causes wood to crack). Ideal storage is at 50-60% humidity.</p>

      <h2>Bellows Care</h2>
      <p>The bellows are made of leather or fabric with folds that allow expansion and contraction. Inspect bellows every 6 months for small cracks or air leaks. Test by opening bellows fully then quickly pressing them — any hissing sound indicates a leak. Small leaks can be patched with bellows repair tape from a music shop. Major bellows damage requires professional repair.</p>

      <h2>Reed Maintenance</h2>
      <p>Reeds (the thin metal tongues that produce sound) require minimal maintenance but can occasionally go out of tune especially in humid climates. If a note starts sounding flat or sharp or buzzes it may need tuning. Reed tuning requires specialized tools and knowledge — take your harmonium to an experienced repair person rather than attempting it yourself initially.</p>

      <h2>When to Seek Professional Service</h2>
      <p>Take your harmonium to a repair technician when: a note stops sounding entirely (reed may be bent or broken), multiple notes go out of tune simultaneously, bellows have major air leaks affecting playability, keys stick or do not spring back properly, or foreign objects have fallen inside the instrument. In major Indian cities specialized harmonium repair shops are available in music districts.</p>

